> - **Module:** Module 1
> - **Topic:** State Management in Flutter: Provider, Riverpod, and BLoC

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 What is "State" in Flutter?

In Flutter, **State** is any data that can change during the lifetime of a widget and that, when changed, triggers a rebuild of the UI to reflect the new value. A `StatelessWidget` never holds mutable state, while a `StatefulWidget` holds mutable state in its `State` object via `setState()`.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Definition (PECST695):** State management is the *strategy and tooling* used to organize, propagate, and synchronize mutable data across the widget tree so that dependent widgets rebuild predictably and efficiently.

### 1.2 Why Do We Need State Management?

When a Flutter app grows beyond a single screen, the internal `setState()` call becomes insufficient because:

- **Prop-drilling** becomes tedious: passing state down 4–5 levels of widgets.
- **Coupling** increases: child widgets must know about the parent's state shape.
- **Scalability** collapses: rebuilding the entire tree for small changes causes jank.

### 1.3 The Three Pillars — At a Glance

| Pattern | Origin | Core Idea |
|---|---|---|
| **Provider** | Remi Rousselet, 2018 (recommended by Flutter team) | InheritedWidget wrapper exposing a `ChangeNotifier` |
| **Riverpod** | Remi Rousselet, 2020 | Compile-safe, testable providers with no BuildContext dependency |
| **BLoC** (Business Logic Component) | Felix Angelov, 2018 (Google) | Unidirectional event → state flow using Streams |

### 1.4 Intuitive Analogy — The Newspaper Kiosk

Imagine your app is a **city**, widgets are **houses**, and state is the **weather**.

- `setState()`: Every house has its own personal rain meter. If it rains, you must tell every house manually. **Exhausting.**
- **Provider**: A central weather tower broadcasts the weather. Houses that **subscribed** get notified automatically. **Good.**
- **Riverpod**: Same weather tower, but houses can subscribe to *specific* weather types (humidity, temperature) without knowing the tower's location. **Better.**
- **BLoC**: A weather department receives **official requests** ("Tell me humidity!"), processes them, and publishes a **weather bulletin**. Houses only read the bulletin. **Most structured.**

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Highlight:** The official Flutter documentation now recommends **Provider as the baseline**, **Riverpod as the modern evolution**, and **BLoC for complex enterprise apps** with heavy business logic.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Provider Pattern — Theoretical Breakdown

**Core Components:**
1. **`ChangeNotifier`** — A class that extends `ChangeNotifier` and calls `notifyListeners()` whenever its data mutates.
2. **`ChangeNotifierProvider`** — A widget that *owns* the `ChangeNotifier` instance and exposes it to descendants.
3. **`Consumer<T>`** — A widget that rebuilds only when `T` notifies.
4. **`context.watch<T>()` / `context.read<T>()`** — Extensions used inside the `build()` method.
   - `watch` → subscribes (rebuilds on change).
   - `read` → one-time lookup (does NOT rebuild).

**Lifecycle Steps:**
- Step 1: Create a class extending `ChangeNotifier`.
- Step 2: Wrap your app's root (or subtree) with `ChangeNotifierProvider`.
- Step 3: Inside any descendant, use `Consumer` or `context.watch` to listen.
- Step 4: Mutate state inside the notifier and call `notifyListeners()`.

### 2.2 The Riverpod Pattern — Theoretical Breakdown

**Why Riverpod Exists:** Provider has a flaw — it depends on `BuildContext`, making it hard to use providers *outside* the widget tree (e.g., in services, tests, or async callbacks).

**Core Components:**
1. **`ProviderScope`** — The root widget that owns all providers.
2. **`Provider` / `StateProvider` / `StateNotifierProvider` / `FutureProvider`** — Declarations of state.
3. **`ConsumerWidget` / `ConsumerStatefulWidget`** — Widgets that can read providers via `ref.watch`, `ref.read`, `ref.listen`.
4. **`Ref<T>` object** — The replacement for `BuildContext`; works anywhere.

**The Three Provider Flavors:**
- `Provider` → immutable value (config, services).
- `StateProvider` → simple mutable value (toggle, counter).
- `StateNotifierProvider` → complex state with methods.

### 2.3 The BLoC Pattern — Theoretical Breakdown

**Philosophy:** Strict separation of **UI** and **Business Logic** using **Streams**.

**Core Components:**
1. **`Event`** — Input from the UI (e.g., `IncrementPressed`).
2. **`State`** — Output to the UI (e.g., `CounterValue(int)`).
3. **`Bloc<Event, State>`** — The brain: receives events, emits states via `emit()`.
4. **`BlocProvider`** — Wraps a subtree and provides the BLoC.
5. **`BlocBuilder`** — Rebuilds on every state change.
6. **`BlocListener`** — Reacts to state changes (e.g., navigation, snackbars) without rebuilding.

**Event Flow:**

```
UI Widget → Dispatch Event → BLoC.onEvent() → emit(State) → BlocBuilder rebuilds UI
```

### 2.4 KTU High-Yield Comparison Cheat Sheet

| Criteria | Provider | Riverpod | BLoC |
|---|---|---|---|
| **State Mechanism** | `ChangeNotifier` + `notifyListeners()` | `StateNotifier` / `Notifier` | `Stream<Event>` → `Stream<State>` |
| **Context Required?** | Yes (uses `BuildContext`) | **No** (uses `Ref`) | No (uses `BlocProvider.of`) |
| **Testability** | Moderate | **Excellent** | **Excellent** |
| **Boilerplate Code** | Low | Low–Medium | **High** |
| **Compile-time Safety** | Runtime | **Compile-time** | Runtime |
| **Best Use Case** | Small–medium apps | Medium–large apps | Enterprise / complex flows |
| **Learning Curve** | Easy | Medium | **Steep** |
| **Recommended By** | Flutter Team (baseline) | Flutter Community | Google (Dart team) |
| **Key Package** | `provider: ^6.x` | `flutter_riverpod: ^2.x` | `flutter_bloc: ^8.x` |
| **Reactive Type** | Listener pattern | Listener + Stream | Pure Stream-based |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Mark Booster:** Examiners often ask: *"Compare Provider, Riverpod, and BLoC."* Memorize the table above — the **Context Required**, **Boilerplate**, and **Best Use Case** rows are the most frequently tested.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Implementation Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> **Why code here?** This is a **CS/Programming course (PECST695)**. Code is the primary assessment medium. The "no Python/coding" rule applies only to non-CS subjects (Maths, Physics, Civil, etc.).

### 3.1 Provider — Counter App (Exhaustive Walkthrough)

**Step 1: Add the dependency** — In `pubspec.yaml`:
```yaml
dependencies:
  flutter:
    sdk: flutter
  provider: ^6.1.2
```

**Step 2: Define the model (the notifier)**
```dart
import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';

class CounterNotifier extends ChangeNotifier {
  int _count = 0;
  int get count => _count;

  void increment() {
    _count++;
    notifyListeners();   // <-- tells all listeners to rebuild
  }

  void decrement() {
    _count--;
    notifyListeners();
  }
}
```

**Step 3: Provide it at the root** — In `main.dart`:
```dart
void main() {
  runApp(
    ChangeNotifierProvider(
      create: (_) => CounterNotifier(),
      child: const MyApp(),
    ),
  );
}
```

**Step 4: Consume it in a widget**
```dart
class CounterPage extends StatelessWidget {
  const CounterPage({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // context.watch subscribes to changes
    final counter = context.watch<CounterNotifier>();

    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Provider Counter')),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Count: ${counter.count}',
            style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 32)),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        onPressed: () => context.read<CounterNotifier>().increment(),
        child: const Icon(Icons.add),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- `context.watch` triggers rebuild when `notifyListeners()` is called.
- `context.read` only *reads* the value once — perfect for callbacks like `onPressed`.
- Using `Consumer` instead is an alternative: `Consumer<CounterNotifier>(builder: (ctx, counter, _) => ...)`.

### 3.2 Riverpod — Counter App (Exhaustive Walkthrough)

**Step 1: Add the dependency**
```yaml
dependencies:
  flutter_riverpod: ^2.5.1
```

**Step 2: Declare the provider (globally, outside any class)**
```dart
import 'package:flutter_riverpod/flutter_riverpod.dart';

final counterProvider = StateNotifierProvider<CounterNotifier, int>((ref) {
  return CounterNotifier();
});

class CounterNotifier extends StateNotifier<int> {
  CounterNotifier() : super(0);   // initial state = 0

  void increment() => state++;
  void decrement() => state--;
}
```

**Step 3: Wrap your app in `ProviderScope`**
```dart
void main() {
  runApp(const ProviderScope(child: MyApp()));
}
```

**Step 4: Consume it using `ConsumerWidget`**
```dart
class CounterPage extends ConsumerWidget {
  const CounterPage({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context, WidgetRef ref) {
    final count = ref.watch(counterProvider);

    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Riverpod Counter')),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Count: $count', style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 32)),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: FloatingActionButton(
        onPressed: () => ref.read(counterProvider.notifier).increment(),
        child: const Icon(Icons.add),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- `StateNotifier<int>` holds the int state. Setting `state = newValue` automatically triggers rebuilds.
- `ref.watch` subscribes; `ref.read` is a one-shot lookup.
- **No `BuildContext` needed** for state — providers are decoupled from the widget tree.

### 3.3 BLoC — Counter App (Exhaustive Walkthrough)

**Step 1: Add the dependency**
```yaml
dependencies:
  flutter_bloc: ^8.1.6
```

**Step 2: Define the event (sealed class)**
```dart
abstract class CounterEvent {}

class IncrementPressed extends CounterEvent {}
class DecrementPressed extends CounterEvent {}
```

**Step 3: Define the state**
```dart
class CounterState {
  final int value;
  const CounterState(this.value);
}
```

**Step 4: Define the BLoC**
```dart
import 'package:flutter_bloc/flutter_bloc.dart';

class CounterBloc extends Bloc<CounterEvent, CounterState> {
  CounterBloc() : super(const CounterState(0)) {
    on<IncrementPressed>((event, emit) {
      emit(CounterState(state.value + 1));
    });

    on<DecrementPressed>((event, emit) {
      emit(CounterState(state.value - 1));
    });
  }
}
```

**Step 5: Provide it in the widget tree**
```dart
void main() {
  runApp(
    BlocProvider(
      create: (_) => CounterBloc(),
      child: const MyApp(),
    ),
  );
}
```

**Step 6: Consume it using `BlocBuilder`**
```dart
class CounterPage extends StatelessWidget {
  const CounterPage({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('BLoC Counter')),
      body: Center(
        child: BlocBuilder<CounterBloc, CounterState>(
          builder: (context, state) {
            return Text('Count: ${state.value}',
                style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 32));
          },
        ),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: Row(
        mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.end,
        children: [
          FloatingActionButton(
            onPressed: () =>
                context.read<CounterBloc>().add(DecrementPressed()),
            child: const Icon(Icons.remove),
          ),
          const SizedBox(width: 16),
          FloatingActionButton(
            onPressed: () =>
                context.read<CounterBloc>().add(IncrementPressed()),
            child: const Icon(Icons.add),
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- The UI never calls the BLoC's methods directly; it **dispatches an Event**.
- The BLoC **maps** events to new states using the `on<Event>()` handler.
- `emit()` pushes the new state into the stream; `BlocBuilder` rebuilds on every new state.

### 3.4 Decision Matrix — When to Use What

$$
\text{Choose pattern} = \begin{cases}
\text{setState} & \text{if state is local to one widget} \\[4pt]
\text{Provider} & \text{if app is small, few global objects} \\[4pt]
\text{Riverpod} & \text{if you want compile-safety and testability} \\[4pt]
\text{BLoC} & \text{if you have complex business logic / audit trail}
\end{cases}
$$

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

