## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
*Define state management in Flutter. Why is `setState()` insufficient for large applications?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
State management is the strategy used to organize and propagate mutable data across the widget tree so that dependent widgets rebuild correctly. `setState()` is insufficient for large apps because (1) it only triggers rebuild of the **owning widget** and requires prop-drilling to pass data to descendants, (2) it tightly couples UI to data, and (3) it does not scale across multiple screens or async data sources. (3 marks for: definition 1 mark + 2 reasons 1 mark each)

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**
*List any three differences between Provider and Riverpod.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
1. **Context Dependency** — Provider requires `BuildContext` to access state; Riverpod uses a `Ref` object and does not need context.
2. **Compile-time Safety** — Riverpod throws errors at compile time if a provider is misused; Provider fails at runtime.
3. **Testability** — Riverpod can be tested without a widget tree using `ProviderContainer`; Provider always needs a `BuildContext`.

(1 mark per valid difference)

---

### Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each)

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning:** Students frequently lose marks by (1) writing code without comments, (2) forgetting `notifyListeners()` / `emit()` in the right place, and (3) confusing `context.watch` with `context.read`. **Always state whether your call subscribes or one-shot reads.**

---

#### **Question A (14 Marks)**
**[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024]**

**(a)** Explain the BLoC pattern in Flutter with a neat block diagram. List its core components. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete Flutter application using the BLoC pattern to implement a counter app that supports Increment, Decrement, and Reset events. Show the Event class, State class, BLoC class, and UI widget. **(7 marks)**

---

#### **Model Answer — Question A**

**(a) BLoC Pattern Explanation (7 marks):**

The **Business Logic Component (BLoC)** pattern, proposed by Felix Angelov, enforces a strict **unidirectional data flow** based on **Streams**. It decouples the presentation layer from business logic.

**Core Components:**
1. **Event** — User intention (e.g., `IncrementPressed`).
2. **State** — Output data (e.g., `CounterState(value: 5)`).
3. **Bloc<Event, State>** — The processor: receives events, applies logic, emits states.
4. **BlocProvider** — Injects the BLoC into the widget tree.
5. **BlocBuilder** — Rebuilds UI on state change.
6. **BlocListener** — Executes side effects (e.g., navigation) without rebuilding.

**Block Diagram (text-based for exam):**

```
[UI Widget] --dispatch Event--> [Bloc.on<Event>()] --emit State--> [Stream<State>]
                                                                              |
                                                              BlocBuilder / Listener
                                                                              |
                                                                       [Rebuild UI]
```

(2 marks for explanation + 2 marks for diagram + 3 marks for components list)

---

**(b) BLoC Counter App Code (7 marks):**

```dart
// Step 1: Event class
abstract class CounterEvent {}
class IncrementPressed extends CounterEvent {}
class DecrementPressed extends CounterEvent {}
class ResetPressed extends CounterEvent {}

// Step 2: State class
class CounterState {
  final int value;
  const CounterState(this.value);
}

// Step 3: BLoC class
class CounterBloc extends Bloc<CounterEvent, CounterState> {
  CounterBloc() : super(const CounterState(0)) {
    on<IncrementPressed>((e, emit) => emit(CounterState(state.value + 1)));
    on<DecrementPressed>((e, emit) => emit(CounterState(state.value - 1)));
    on<ResetPressed>((e, emit) => emit(const CounterState(0)));
  }
}

// Step 4: Provide BLoC at root
void main() => runApp(
  BlocProvider(create: (_) => CounterBloc(), child: const MyApp()),
);

// Step 5: UI using BlocBuilder
class CounterPage extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('BLoC Counter')),
      body: Center(
        child: BlocBuilder<CounterBloc, CounterState>(
          builder: (_, state) =>
              Text('Count: ${state.value}',
                   style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 32)),
        ),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: Row(
        mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.end,
        children: [
          FloatingActionButton(
            onPressed: () => context.read<CounterBloc>().add(ResetPressed()),
            child: const Icon(Icons.refresh),
          ),
          const SizedBox(width: 8),
          FloatingActionButton(
            onPressed: () => context.read<CounterBloc>().add(DecrementPressed()),
            child: const Icon(Icons.remove),
          ),
          const SizedBox(width: 8),
          FloatingActionButton(
            onPressed: () => context.read<CounterBloc>().add(IncrementPressed()),
            child: const Icon(Icons.add),
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

(2 marks for Event/State, 2 marks for BLoC class, 2 marks for UI integration, 1 mark for proper dispatching via `add()`)

---

#### **Question B (14 Marks) [Alternative Choice]**
**[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024]**

**(a)** Compare Provider, Riverpod, and BLoC in terms of (i) state mechanism, (ii) testability, (iii) boilerplate, and (iv) best use case. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Implement a counter application using **Riverpod** with `StateNotifierProvider`. Show the provider declaration, notifier class, `ProviderScope` setup, and a `ConsumerWidget` UI. **(7 marks)**

---

#### **Model Answer — Question B**

**(a) Comparison Table (7 marks):**

| Criteria | Provider | Riverpod | BLoC |
|---|---|---|---|
| **State Mechanism** | `ChangeNotifier` + `notifyListeners()` | `StateNotifier` / `Notifier` (auto-rebuild on `state=`) | `Stream<Event>` → `Stream<State>` via `emit()` |
| **Testability** | Moderate — needs `BuildContext` | **Excellent** — `ProviderContainer` works without UI | **Excellent** — pure Dart, no UI needed |
| **Boilerplate** | Low | Low–Medium | **High** (Event + State + BLoC classes) |
| **Best Use Case** | Small–medium apps with few global objects | Medium–large apps needing compile-safety | Enterprise apps with complex flows and audit trail |

(1.5 marks per row × 4 rows = 6 marks + 1 mark for clean tabular format)

---

**(b) Riverpod Counter Implementation (7 marks):**

```dart
// Step 1: Provider declaration
final counterProvider =
    StateNotifierProvider<CounterNotifier, int>((ref) => CounterNotifier());

// Step 2: Notifier class
class CounterNotifier extends StateNotifier<int> {
  CounterNotifier() : super(0);
  void increment() => state++;
  void decrement() => state--;
  void reset() => state = 0;
}

// Step 3: Wrap with ProviderScope
void main() => runApp(const ProviderScope(child: MyApp()));

// Step 4: ConsumerWidget UI
class CounterPage extends ConsumerWidget {
  const CounterPage({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context, WidgetRef ref) {
    final count = ref.watch(counterProvider);
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Riverpod Counter')),
      body: Center(
        child: Text('Count: $count',
                    style: const TextStyle(fontSize: 32)),
      ),
      floatingActionButton: Row(
        mainAxisAlignment: MainAxisAlignment.end,
        children: [
          IconButton(
            onPressed: () => ref.read(counterProvider.notifier).reset(),
            icon: const Icon(Icons.refresh),
          ),
          IconButton(
            onPressed: () => ref.read(counterProvider.notifier).decrement(),
            icon: const Icon(Icons.remove),
          ),
          IconButton(
            onPressed: () => ref.read(counterProvider.notifier).increment(),
            icon: const Icon(Icons.add),
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

(2 marks for provider declaration, 2 marks for notifier with state mutation, 2 marks for ConsumerWidget, 1 mark for ProviderScope wrapping)

---

### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ **State** = mutable data that triggers UI rebuilds.
- ✅ **Provider** = `ChangeNotifier` + `ChangeNotifierProvider` + `Consumer` / `context.watch`.
- ✅ **Riverpod** = compile-safe, **no `BuildContext` required**, uses `ref.watch` / `ref.read`.
- ✅ **BLoC** = unidirectional **Event → Bloc → State** flow using Streams.
- ✅ Always call `notifyListeners()` in Provider; just assign `state = value` in Riverpod; call `emit()` in BLoC.
- ✅ `context.watch` / `ref.watch` **subscribes**; `context.read` / `ref.read` **does not**.
- ✅ Choose **BLoC** for enterprise, **Riverpod** for modern medium-scale, **Provider** for small apps.
- ✅ `ProviderScope` is mandatory at the root for Riverpod; `BlocProvider` for BLoC.
- ✅ **Exam Tip:** When asked to "implement", you MUST show: dependency addition + model + provider + UI.
- ✅ **Common Pitfall:** Forgetting `notifyListeners()` (Provider) or calling methods instead of `add(Event)` (BLoC).
- ✅ **KTU Weightage:** State Management typically carries **12–14 marks** in the ESE (End Semester Exam).
<!-- SECTION_5_END -->

