# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The HTTP Request–Response Lifecycle (Deconstructed)

Every network operation in Flutter follows a **strict 7-stage pipeline**. The `http` package abstracts most of this, but understanding the underlying mechanics is essential for debugging and for KTU theory questions.

1. **DNS Resolution** — The domain name (e.g., `api.github.com`) is resolved into an IP address via the Domain Name System.
2. **TCP Handshake (3-Way)** — `SYN → SYN-ACK → ACK` establishes a reliable connection (HTTPS adds a **TLS handshake**).
3. **Request Construction** — The Flutter app builds a `Request` object containing:
   - **URL** (endpoint)
   - **Method** (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`, `PATCH`)
   - **Headers** (metadata: `Content-Type`, `Authorization`)
   - **Body** (optional payload, usually JSON)
4. **Server Processing** — The remote server authenticates, authorizes, and computes a response.
5. **Response Transmission** — Server returns a status line + headers + body.
6. **JSON Decoding** — Dart's `json.decode()` parses the response string into `Map<String, dynamic>` or `List<dynamic>`.
7. **State Update** — UI widgets (typically via `setState`, `FutureBuilder`, or `Provider`) re-render with the new data.

---

## 2.2 HTTP Methods — The Standard Verbs

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Topic:** Examiners frequently ask students to "list and explain HTTP methods". Memorize the table below.

| Method | Idempotent? | Safe? | Body? | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `GET` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | Fetch a resource (read-only) |
| `POST` | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | Create a new resource |
| `PUT` | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | Replace an existing resource entirely |
| `PATCH` | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | Partially update a resource |
| `DELETE` | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ Optional | Remove a resource |

> *Idempotent* = repeating the call produces the same result.
> *Safe* = does not modify server state.

---

## 2.3 HTTP Status Codes — The Server's Verdict

> [!NOTE]
> **The five classes every Flutter developer must know:**

| Class | Range | Meaning | Common Examples |
|---|---|---|---|
| **1xx Informational** | 100–199 | Request received, continuing process | `100 Continue` |
| **2xx Success** | 200–299 | Request succeeded | `200 OK`, `201 Created`, `204 No Content` |
| **3xx Redirection** | 300–399 | Further action needed | `301 Moved Permanently`, `304 Not Modified` |
| **4xx Client Error** | 400–499 | Fault in the request | `400 Bad Request`, `401 Unauthorized`, `403 Forbidden`, `404 Not Found` |
| **5xx Server Error** | 500–599 | Server failed to fulfill valid request | `500 Internal Server Error`, `503 Service Unavailable` |

---

## 2.4 JSON Syntax — The Anatomy

JSON supports exactly **six data types**:

$$
\text{JSON Value} ::= \text{null} \mid \text{true} \mid \text{false} \mid \text{number} \mid \text{string} \mid \text{array} \mid \text{object}
$$

A typical API response looks like this:

```json
{
  "userId": 101,
  "name": "Ananya Krishnan",
  "isVerified": true,
  "balance": 4520.75,
  "tags": ["premium", "kerala", "flutter-dev"],
  "address": {
    "city": "Kochi",
    "pincode": 682021
  },
  "lastLogin": null
}
```

---

## 2.5 The Six REST Architectural Constraints (Fielding, 2000)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Mandatory KTU Theory Point:** REST was defined by **Roy Fielding** in his 2000 dissertation. The six constraints are examinable.

1. **Client–Server Architecture** — Separation of concerns; UI and storage evolve independently.
2. **Statelessness** — Each request contains *all* information needed; the server stores no client session.
3. **Cacheability** — Responses must explicitly state whether they are cacheable to improve performance.
4. **Layered System** — Client cannot tell whether it is talking to the end server or an intermediary (proxy, load balancer).
5. **Uniform Interface** — Standardized resource identification (URIs), standard methods, standard representations (HATEOAS).
6. **Code-on-Demand** *(optional)* — Server can send executable code (e.g., JavaScript) to client.

---

## 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| # | Concept | Notation / API Call | Purpose / Engineering Use |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | HTTP GET | `http.get(Uri.parse(url))` | Read data from server |
| 2 | HTTP POST | `http.post(uri, headers: {...}, body: jsonEncode(data))` | Submit new data |
| 3 | HTTP PUT | `http.put(uri, body: jsonEncode(data))` | Update entire resource |
| 4 | HTTP DELETE | `http.delete(uri)` | Remove a resource |
| 5 | JSON Decode | `json.decode(response.body)` | Parse string into `Map<String, dynamic>` |
| 6 | JSON Encode | `json.encode(dartObject)` | Convert Dart object to JSON string |
| 7 | Async GET helper | `await http.get(uri)` | Suspends execution until response arrives |
| 8 | Status check | `if (response.statusCode == 200)` | Validate success before parsing |
| 9 | Error catch | `catch (e) { ... } catch (SocketException) ...` | Handle network failures |
| 10 | Timeout | `Future.delayed(Duration(seconds: 10))` | Bound waiting time |

---

## 2.7 The `http` Package — Why It's the Standard

The official `http` package (maintained by the Dart team on `pub.dev`) provides:
- **Promise/Future-based asynchronous API** — non-blocking I/O.
- **Cross-platform** support — Android, iOS, Web, Desktop.
- **Interceptor support** (via `http.Client` subclassing).
- **Built-in streaming** via `http.StreamedResponse`.

> *Recent versions of Flutter (3.x+) also feature `dio` as an alternative, but the `http` package is the KTU-recommended baseline.*

