### Question B `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]` *(Alternative to Question A)*

**a)** Compare **synchronous vs asynchronous programming** in Dart. Why is `async`/`await` essential for network calls? Demonstrate with a Flutter `http.get()` example. **(7 marks)**

**b)** Explain the **HTTP status code classes** (1xx–5xx). For each class, give the meaning and **one realistic example** showing how a Flutter app should react to that status code. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution (a) — Sync vs Async in Dart

**Synchronous Programming:**
- Code executes **line-by-line, in order**, blocking the current thread until each operation completes.
- A long operation (e.g., a 5-second HTTP request) **freezes the entire UI** until it returns.
- Suitable only for **CPU-bound, instantaneous** tasks.

**Asynchronous Programming:**
- Long-running operations are **scheduled and the thread continues executing other code**.
- When the operation completes, a callback or `Future` resumes the suspended code.
- In Flutter, the UI thread must never be blocked — hence **all I/O is async**.

**Why `async`/`await` for network calls:**

The `http.get()` method returns a `Future<http.Response>`. Without `async`/`await`, we would have to chain `.then()` and `.catchError()` callbacks, leading to "callback hell". With `async`/`await`, we write asynchronous code that **looks and reads like synchronous code**.

**Demonstration:**

```dart
// WITHOUT async/await — callback style
void fetchWithoutAsync() {
  http
      .get(Uri.parse('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1'))
      .then((response) {
        print('Status: ${response.statusCode}');
        print('Body: ${response.body}');
      })
      .catchError((error) {
        print('Error: $error');
      });
  print('This prints BEFORE the response arrives');
}

// WITH async/await — clean linear style
Future<void> fetchWithAsync() async {
  try {
    final response = await http
        .get(Uri.parse('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1'))
        .timeout(const Duration(seconds: 10));
    print('Status: ${response.statusCode}');
    print('Body: ${response.body}');
  } catch (e) {
    print('Error: $e');
  }
}
```

**Key observations:**
- In the first snippet, `"This prints BEFORE..."` runs first because `.get()` is non-blocking.
- In the second snippet, the `await` **suspends** the function until the future completes, but **does not block the event loop**, so the UI remains responsive.

*(7 marks — 2 marks comparison, 2 marks rationale, 3 marks code example.)*

---

#### Model Solution (b) — HTTP Status Code Classes

| Class | Range | Meaning | Realistic Example | Flutter App Reaction |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **1xx Informational** | 100–199 | Provisional response; request received, continuing. | `100 Continue` | Typically handled by HTTP client transparently; no app logic needed. |
| **2xx Success** | 200–299 | Request succeeded. | `200 OK` from GET /users | Show the data, hide loading spinner. |
| | | | `201 Created` from POST /users | Show "User created successfully" snackbar. |
| | | | `204 No Content` from DELETE /users/5 | Show "Deleted" snackbar, refresh list. |
| **3xx Redirection** | 300–399 | Client must take additional action. | `301 Moved Permanently` — old API URL moved. | The `http` package follows redirects by default; no manual action required. |
| **4xx Client Error** | 400–499 | The request was malformed or unauthorized. | `400 Bad Request` — invalid JSON body. | Show "Invalid input" error. |
| | | | `401 Unauthorized` — missing/invalid token. | Redirect user to login screen. |
| | | | `404 Not Found` — invalid endpoint or resource ID. | Show "Resource not found" empty state. |
| **5xx Server Error** | 500–599 | Server failed to fulfill a valid request. | `500 Internal Server Error` | Show "Something went wrong on our end, please retry later." with a retry button. |
| | | | `503 Service Unavailable` — server under maintenance. | Show "Service is temporarily down" message. |

**General Flutter pattern for handling status codes:**

```dart
if (response.statusCode >= 200 && response.statusCode < 300) {
  // Success branch
} else if (response.statusCode == 401) {
  // Auth branch — refresh token or redirect to login
} else if (response.statusCode >= 500) {
  // Server error branch — show generic retry
} else {
  // Other client errors — show specific message
}
```

*(7 marks — 1 mark per class description + example + reaction.)*

