## 📌 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **HTTP** is the request-response protocol; **HTTPS** adds TLS encryption on port **443**.
- The **three Flutter networking essentials** are: the `http` package, the `dart:convert` library for JSON, and `FutureBuilder`/`async`/`await` for UI integration.
- HTTP methods are **GET (read), POST (create), PUT (replace), PATCH (partial update), DELETE (remove)**.
- **2xx = success, 4xx = client error, 5xx = server error** — memorize the most common codes.
- **JSON** supports six data types: `null`, `boolean`, `number`, `string`, `array`, `object`.
- `json.encode()` → Dart-to-JSON-string; `json.decode()` → JSON-string-to-Dart.
- **Model classes** with `factory Model.fromJson(Map)` enforce type safety when parsing.
- **Always check `response.statusCode`** before decoding the body.
- **Always wrap network calls in try-catch** to handle `SocketException`, `HttpException`, `FormatException`, and `TimeoutException`.
- **Always set `.timeout(...)`** on long-running requests.
- **Always close the `http.Client`** in the widget's `dispose()` method to prevent memory leaks.
- **Internet permissions** must be declared in `AndroidManifest.xml` and `Info.plist`.
- **REST** = architectural style by **Roy Fielding (2000)**; six constraints — Client–Server, Stateless, Cacheable, Layered System, Uniform Interface, Code-on-Demand.
- **Statelessness** is the most important REST constraint — every request must carry all necessary info.
- **FutureBuilder** has three states: `waiting`, `hasData`, `hasError` — handle all three in the `builder` callback.
- **Never place network calls inside `build()`** — only in `initState()` or event handlers.
- **REST vs SOAP**: REST is resource-oriented, lightweight, uses HTTP verbs and JSON; SOAP is action-oriented, heavy, uses XML envelopes and WSDL.
- **Idempotent** methods (GET, PUT, DELETE) produce the same result on repeated calls; **non-idempotent** methods (POST, PATCH) may produce different results.

