# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield "Cheat Sheet"

## 2.1 The Three Layers of a Mobile App's Data Architecture

Every mobile app can be decomposed into three concentric layers. The KTU examiner will expect you to draw this triangle and label each layer in your viva/project review.

```
        ┌─────────────────────────┐
        │   PRESENTATION LAYER    │  ← Widgets / Screens / Pages
        │   (Stateless UI)        │
        └────────────┬────────────┘
                     │ reads & triggers events
        ┌────────────▼────────────┐
        │  STATE / BUSINESS LOGIC │  ← Providers, BLoCs, Controllers
        │       LAYER             │
        └────────────┬────────────┘
                     │ reads & writes
        ┌────────────▼────────────┐
        │      DATA LAYER         │  ← Repositories, DB, Network, Prefs
        │  (Persistence + API)    │
        └─────────────────────────┘
```

### 2.2 State Management — The Four Major Patterns

The KTU 2024 syllabus for PECST695 expects familiarity with **at least two** of the following patterns. You must compare them in the exam.

| Pattern | Mechanism | When to Use | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **`setState`** | Local `State.setState((){...})` | One widget, no sharing | Zero setup, fastest | Not scalable, rebuilds everything visible |
| **Provider / `ChangeNotifier`** | Inherited widget that exposes a `ChangeNotifier`; widgets call `notifyListeners()` | Small-to-medium apps | Official Flutter package, simple | Can cause over-rebuilds if used carelessly |
| **Riverpod** | Providers that are *outside* the widget tree; uses `ref.watch`/`ref.read` | Medium-to-large apps | Compile-safe, no `BuildContext` coupling | Steeper learning curve |
| **BLoC / Cubit** | Events → State streams via `Stream` | Large apps, teams | Highly testable, predictable | Verbose, requires code generation |
| **GetX** | Reactive `.obs` variables + `Obx()` | Rapid prototyping | Very concise | Breaks separation of concerns if abused |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Recommended Default for Module 1 Project:** Use **`Provider` + `ChangeNotifier`** *or* **Riverpod**. They are officially recommended, widely taught, and integrate cleanly with persistence layers.

### 2.3 Data Persistence — The Five Major Options

| Option | Type | Capacity | Speed | Best For |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **`SharedPreferences`** | Key-Value (XML/plist on Android/iOS) | < 1 MB | ⚡⚡⚡⚡⚡ | Theme, language, simple flags |
| **`Hive` (NoSQL)** | Key-Value, NoSQL boxes | GB scale | ⚡⚡⚡⚡ | Offline-first apps, complex objects |
| **`sqflite` (SQL)** | Relational SQLite | GB scale | ⚡⚡⚡ | Structured data, queries, joins |
| **File I/O** | Plain text / binary files | Unlimited | ⚡⚡ | Logs, JSON exports, images |
| **`path_provider` + JSON** | Custom JSON file | Unlimited | ⚡⚡ | Small config files, backups |

> [!WARNING]
> Never use `SharedPreferences` to store lists of complex objects. KTU examiners will deduct marks because it violates the Single Responsibility Principle and blocks scalability.

### 2.4 The "KTU High-Yield" Cheat Sheet — Boxes You Must Draw

#### Box A: State Management Decision Matrix

```
Is the state used by ONE widget only?
   ├─ YES → use setState()
   └─ NO  → Is the app small (< 5 screens)?
              ├─ YES → Provider / ChangeNotifier
              └─ NO  → Do you need testability & events?
                          ├─ YES → BLoC / Cubit
                          └─ NO  → Riverpod
```

#### Box B: Persistence Decision Matrix

```
Is the data a primitive flag (bool, int, String)?
   ├─ YES → SharedPreferences
   └─ NO  → Is the data structured (multiple fields, relations)?
              ├─ YES → sqflite (SQL)
              └─ NO  → Hive (NoSQL boxes)
                       └─ Is it just a config blob?
                             └─ YES → JSON file via path_provider
```

### 2.5 The CRUD Contract — Every Persistent Entity Must Implement It

For **every** entity in your project (e.g., `Note`, `Task`, `Expense`), you must expose:

| Operation | Method Signature (Dart pseudocode) | Returns |
|---|---|---|
| **Create** | `Future<int> add(Entity e)` | row id / new id |
| **Read All** | `Future<List<Entity>> getAll()` | list |
| **Read One** | `Future<Entity?> getById(int id)` | nullable entity |
| **Update** | `Future<int> update(Entity e)` | rows affected |
| **Delete** | `Future<int> delete(int id)` | rows affected |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> In your KTU project review, the examiner will ask: *"Show me your CRUD interface."* If you cannot produce a clean repository abstraction, **2 to 3 marks will be cut**.

### 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **State management** prevents the *most expensive class of bugs* in mobile apps — UI desynchronization. A button click that should disable a spinner but doesn't, a list that doesn't refresh after a delete, a form that loses data on rotation — all are state management failures.
- **Data persistence** is the *core of every offline-capable app*. Google Maps caches tiles, WhatsApp caches messages, Spotify caches songs — none of these would work without sophisticated persistence.
- Together, they form the **backbone of every production mobile app** shipped on the Play Store or App Store.

