# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation Walkthrough & Analytical Matrix

> [!NOTE]
> Because this is a *project* topic (not a theorem), the "derivation" is replaced by a **complete, end-to-end implementation walkthrough** of a sample app — a **"Notes App"** — which you can adapt for your actual KTU submission. Every line is justified.

## 3.1 Project Specification (Reusable for Any KTU Module-1 Submission)

**App Name:** `ktu_notes`
**Goal:** A user can create, read, update, and delete personal notes. Notes survive app restarts. State is managed reactively.
**Stack:** Flutter 3.x + Dart 3.x + `provider` + `sqflite` + `path` + `path_provider`

### Step 1 — Create the Project

```bash
flutter create ktu_notes
cd ktu_notes
flutter pub add provider sqflite path path_provider
```

**Why each dependency?**
- `provider` → reactive state management via `ChangeNotifier`.
- `sqflite` → local relational database.
- `path` & `path_provider` → resolve the platform-correct database folder.

### Step 2 — Define the Data Model (`lib/models/note.dart`)

```dart
class Note {
  final int? id;
  final String title;
  final String body;
  final DateTime createdAt;

  Note({this.id, required this.title, required this.body, required this.createdAt});

  // Convert a Note → Map (for INSERT/UPDATE)
  Map<String, dynamic> toMap() {
    return {
      'id': id,
      'title': title,
      'body': body,
      'created_at': createdAt.toIso8601String(),
    };
  }

  // Convert a Map → Note (for SELECT)
  factory Note.fromMap(Map<String, dynamic> map) {
    return Note(
      id: map['id'] as int?,
      title: map['title'] as String,
      body: map['body'] as String,
      createdAt: DateTime.parse(map['created_at'] as String),
    );
  }
}
```

**Justification:**
- `toMap()` and `fromMap()` are the **serialization contract** between Dart objects and SQL rows.
- `id?` is nullable because a *new* note has no DB id yet (auto-increment assigns it).

### Step 3 — Build the Database Helper (`lib/data/database_helper.dart`)

```dart
import 'package:sqflite/sqflite.dart';
import 'package:path/path.dart' as p;

class DatabaseHelper {
  static final DatabaseHelper instance = DatabaseHelper._init();
  static Database? _database;

  DatabaseHelper._init();

  Future<Database> get database async {
    if (_database != null) return _database!;
    _database = await _initDB('notes.db');
    return _database!;
  }

  Future<Database> _initDB(String fileName) async {
    final dbPath = await getDatabasesPath();
    final path = p.join(dbPath, fileName);

    return await openDatabase(
      path,
      version: 1,
      onCreate: _createDB,
    );
  }

  Future<void> _createDB(Database db, int version) async {
    await db.execute('''
      CREATE TABLE notes (
        id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
        title TEXT NOT NULL,
        body TEXT NOT NULL,
        created_at TEXT NOT NULL
      )
    ''');
  }

  Future<int> insertNote(Map<String, dynamic> note) async {
    final db = await database;
    return await db.insert('notes', note);
  }

  Future<List<Map<String, dynamic>>> getAllNotes() async {
    final db = await database;
    return await db.query('notes', orderBy: 'created_at DESC');
  }

  Future<int> updateNote(Map<String, dynamic> note) async {
    final db = await database;
    return await db.update(
      'notes', note, where: 'id = ?', whereArgs: [note['id']],
    );
  }

  Future<int> deleteNote(int id) async {
    final db = await database;
    return await db.delete('notes', where: 'id = ?', whereArgs: [id]);
  }
}
```

**Why a Singleton?**
- Opening multiple `Database` instances to the same SQLite file is **a runtime error in sqflite**. The singleton guarantees exactly one `Database` object per app process.

**Why the `_createDB` callback?**
- It runs **only once**, the first time the DB file is created. It defines the schema (`notes` table with 4 columns).

### Step 4 — Build the Repository (`lib/data/note_repository.dart`)

```dart
import 'note.dart';
import 'database_helper.dart';

class NoteRepository {
  final DatabaseHelper _db = DatabaseHelper.instance;

  Future<int> create(Note note) =>
      _db.insertNote(note.toMap()..remove('id'));

  Future<List<Note>> readAll() async {
    final maps = await _db.getAllNotes();
    return maps.map(Note.fromMap).toList();
  }

  Future<int> update(Note note) =>
      _db.updateNote(note.toMap());

  Future<int> delete(int id) => _db.deleteNote(id);
}
```

**Why a Repository?**
- It **decouples** the UI/state layer from the database implementation. If tomorrow you swap `sqflite` for Hive or a remote REST API, only the repository changes — the UI does not.

### Step 5 — Build the State Manager (`lib/state/notes_view_model.dart`)

```dart
import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';
import '../data/note_repository.dart';
import '../models/note.dart';

class NotesViewModel extends ChangeNotifier {
  final NoteRepository _repo;
  List<Note> _notes = [];
  bool _isLoading = false;

  NotesViewModel(this._repo);

  List<Note> get notes => _notes;
  bool get isLoading => _isLoading;

  Future<void> loadNotes() async {
    _isLoading = true;
    notifyListeners();                  // (1) show spinner
    _notes = await _repo.readAll();
    _isLoading = false;
    notifyListeners();                  // (2) show data
  }

  Future<void> addNote(String title, String body) async {
    final note = Note(
      title: title,
      body: body,
      createdAt: DateTime.now(),
    );
    await _repo.create(note);
    await loadNotes();                  // refresh
  }

  Future<void> updateNote(Note old, String title, String body) async {
    final updated = Note(
      id: old.id,
      title: title,
      body: body,
      createdAt: old.createdAt,
    );
    await _repo.update(updated);
    await loadNotes();
  }

  Future<void> deleteNote(int id) async {
    await _repo.delete(id);
    await loadNotes();
  }
}
```

**Why `ChangeNotifier`?**
- It is the **canonical reactive primitive** in Flutter for the Provider pattern. Calling `notifyListeners()` triggers every widget that called `context.watch<NotesViewModel>()` to rebuild.

### Step 6 — Wire the State Manager into the App (`lib/main.dart`)

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:provider/provider.dart';
import 'data/note_repository.dart';
import 'state/notes_view_model.dart';
import 'ui/notes_list_screen.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const KtuNotesApp());
}

class KtuNotesApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const KtuNotesApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ChangeNotifierProvider(
      create: (_) => NotesViewModel(NoteRepository())..loadNotes(),
      child: MaterialApp(
        title: 'KTU Notes',
        theme: ThemeData(primarySwatch: Colors.indigo),
        home: const NotesListScreen(),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Why `..loadNotes()` (cascade)?**
- The cascade `..` calls `loadNotes()` on the freshly created `NotesViewModel` *immediately after construction*, so the first frame already shows a spinner → then the data.

### Step 7 — Build the UI — List Screen (`lib/ui/notes_list_screen.dart`)

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
