## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, with Internal Choice)

### Question A — `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2024 Expected Pattern]`

**(a)** *Explain the **three-layer architecture** (Presentation, State, Data) of a Flutter mobile application with a neat diagram. How does this separation improve testability and maintainability?* **(7 marks)**

**(b)** *Design and explain the **complete CRUD workflow** for a "Notes" feature using `sqflite` and `Provider`. Provide the model class, repository, view-model, and a sequence of method calls triggered when a user adds a note.* **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

The three-layer architecture decomposes an app into:

1. **Presentation Layer** — Composed of `StatelessWidget` and `StatefulWidget` classes. It *only* renders data and forwards user events. It holds **no business logic** and **no SQL**.
2. **State / View-Model Layer** — Holds reactive state (`ChangeNotifier`, `Bloc`, `Cubit`). It receives events from the UI, calls the data layer, and notifies the UI of changes.
3. **Data Layer** — Repositories and database/network helpers. It owns the **CRUD** implementation against `sqflite`, `Hive`, REST APIs, etc.

**Benefits:**
- **Testability:** The view-model can be unit-tested without rendering any UI; the repository can be tested without Flutter at all.
- **Maintainability:** Swapping `sqflite` for Hive requires changing only the data layer.
- **Parallel Development:** One developer writes UI while another writes the database layer.

*(Diagram: see Section 4.1 above.)*

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

The complete CRUD workflow for "Notes":

**1. Model (`Note` class):** Holds `id`, `title`, `body`, `createdAt`. Provides `toMap()` and `fromMap()` for SQL serialization. *(2 marks)*

**2. Repository (`NoteRepository`):** Wraps `DatabaseHelper`. Exposes `create()`, `readAll()`, `update()`, `delete(int id)`. Decouples the view-model from sqflite. *(2 marks)*

**3. View-Model (`NotesViewModel extends ChangeNotifier`):**
- Holds `List<Note> _notes` and `bool _isLoading`.
- `loadNotes()` calls `_repo.readAll()`, notifies listeners.
- `addNote(title, body)` constructs a `Note`, calls `_repo.create(note)`, then calls `loadNotes()` to refresh. *(2 marks)*

**4. UI Integration:**
- `main.dart` wraps `MaterialApp` with `ChangeNotifierProvider(create: (_) => NotesViewModel(NoteRepository())..loadNotes())`.
- `NotesListScreen` uses `context.watch<NotesViewModel>()` to rebuild on every `notifyListeners()` call.
- When the user taps the save icon in `NoteEditorScreen`, it calls `context.read<NotesViewModel>().addNote(...)`. *(1 mark)*

*(Sequence diagram: see Section 4.2 above.)*

---

### Question B — `[KTU University Exam – Internal Choice Alt]`

**(a)** *Compare and contrast **at least three Flutter state management patterns** (`setState`, `Provider/ChangeNotifier`, `Riverpod`, `BLoC`). Draw a decision flowchart recommending one for (i) a single-screen counter app and (ii) a multi-screen e-commerce app.* **(7 marks)**

**(b)** *Implement a complete Flutter code-snippet (skeleton acceptable) showing how to **persist a "theme mode" setting using `SharedPreferences`** and **read it on app startup to apply the correct theme**. Also explain why `SharedPreferences` is *not* suitable for storing lists of complex objects.* **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution — Part (a)

**Comparison Table:**

| Aspect | `setState` | `Provider` | `Riverpod` | `BLoC` |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Scope | Local widget | App-wide | App-wide | App-wide |
| Boilerplate | Low | Low | Medium | High |
| Testability | Hard | Easy | Easy | Excellent |
| Learning Curve | Trivial | Easy | Medium | Steep |
| Compile Safety | N/A | Runtime | Compile-time | Compile-time |

**Decision Flowchart:** (see Section 4.3 above)

- **(i) Single-screen counter app → `setState()`** — minimal scope, single widget, no sharing.
- **(ii) Multi-screen e-commerce app → `BLoC` or `Riverpod`** — multiple screens share cart, auth, wishlist, filters. Need testability and clean event-driven design.

*(7 marks distributed: 3 for comparison, 2 for flowchart, 2 for recommendations with justifications.)*

#### Model Solution — Part (b)

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:shared_preferences/shared_preferences.dart';

void main() async {
  WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized();
  final prefs = await SharedPreferences.getInstance();
  final isDark = prefs.getBool('isDark') ?? false;

  runApp(MyApp(isDark: isDark));
}

class MyApp extends StatefulWidget {
  final bool isDark;
  const MyApp({super.key, required this.isDark});

  @override
  State<MyApp> createState() => _MyAppState();
}

class _MyAppState extends State<MyApp> {
  late bool _isDark;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _isDark = widget.isDark;
  }

  Future<void> _toggle() async {
    setState(() => _isDark = !_isDark);
    final prefs = await SharedPreferences.getInstance();
    await prefs.setBool('isDark', _isDark);
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      theme: ThemeData.light(),
      darkTheme: ThemeData.dark(),
      themeMode: _isDark ? ThemeMode.dark : ThemeMode.light,
      home: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('Theme Demo')),
        body: Center(
          child: Switch(
            value: _isDark,
            onChanged: (_) => _toggle(),
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Why `SharedPreferences` is unsuitable for lists of complex objects:**
1. It is intended only for **primitives** (`bool`, `int`, `double`, `String`, `List<String>`). Storing a `List<Note>` requires manual `jsonEncode(jsonDecode(...))`, which is brittle and slow.
2. It loads the **entire file into memory** at startup — degrades performance as data grows.
3. It supports **no queries, no joins, no indexes** — O(N) linear scans only.
4. It has **no migration framework** — schema changes are painful.

For complex objects, use `sqflite` (structured queries) or `Hive` (typed boxes).

*(7 marks: 2 for code skeleton, 2 for explanation, 2 for "why not", 1 for correct `WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized()` call.)*

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Calling `db.execute()` inside `build()`** — instant 3-mark penalty. Always do DB work in async functions called from `initState` or button handlers.
> 2. **Forgetting `WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized()`** before any async plugin call in `main()` — the app crashes on startup.
> 3. **Storing Dart objects directly in `SharedPreferences`** — the compiler allows it (via `setString` + JSON), but the *design* is wrong. Examiners deduct 2 marks for poor persistence choice.
> 4. **Not disposing `TextEditingController`s** — memory leak. 1 mark lost.
> 5. **Mixing UI and DB in the same class** — violates separation of concerns. 2–4 marks lost.
> 6. **Using `setState` for app-wide state** — works but is **anti-pattern**. Examiners expect you to recognize and justify the trade-off.

