## 5.3 Topic Recap — Rapid-Revision Checklist

- **State** = any data that changes over time and influences the UI.
- **State management** = the discipline of holding, mutating, propagating state predictably.
- **Persistence** = data surviving app closure/device restart.
- The **3-layer architecture** (Presentation, State, Data) is the KTU-approved structure for every Flutter app.
- **Five persistence options:** `SharedPreferences`, `Hive`, `sqflite`, File I/O, JSON files.
- **Four state management patterns:** `setState`, `Provider/ChangeNotifier`, `Riverpod`, `BLoC/Cubit`.
- Every persistent entity needs a **CRUD contract**: `create`, `readAll`, `update`, `delete`.
- Use **`Repository` pattern** to decouple UI from database choice.
- Use **`Singleton`** for `DatabaseHelper` to prevent multiple `openDatabase()` calls.
- Always call **`WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized()`** before any async plugin work in `main()`.
- Always **`dispose()`** `TextEditingController`s, `AnimationController`s, and `StreamSubscription`s.
- **`notifyListeners()`** triggers rebuilds in every `context.watch<…>()` consumer.
- **`context.watch`** = rebuild on changes; **`context.read`** = one-shot read, no rebuild.
- **`setState()`** is fine for **single-widget, local** state only.
- **`sqflite` requires schema definition** in `onCreate` callback.
- **JSON serialization** (`toMap`/`fromMap`) is the bridge between Dart objects and SQL rows.
- **`Dismissible`** widget + `onDismissed` callback = swipe-to-delete pattern in 5 lines.
- **Hot reload** keeps state; **hot restart** resets it — useful during development of persistence code.
- **Common marks-losing pitfalls:** calling DB in `build()`, missing `ensureInitialized()`, not disposing controllers, storing complex objects in `SharedPreferences`, mixing UI and DB layers.

