## 3. Step-by-Step Architectural Analysis & Implementation Matrix

### 3.1 Architectural Layer Model for Milestone 3

A production mobile app following KTU 2024 standards is structured in **clean architectural layers**:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  PRESENTATION LAYER                                │
│  • UI Screens (StatelessWidget / Composables)       │
│  • ViewModels / Controllers / Notifiers             │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  DOMAIN LAYER (Business Logic)                      │
│  • UseCases / Repositories                          │
│  • Entities / Models                                │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  DATA LAYER                                         │
│  ┌─────────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────┐ │
│  │  Local Source   │  │   Remote Source           │ │
│  │  (SQLite/Hive)  │  │  (REST API / Firebase)   │ │
│  └─────────────────┘  └──────────────────────────┘ │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### 3.2 State Management — Detailed Provider Pattern Walkthrough (Flutter Example)

The **Provider pattern** uses `InheritedWidget` under the hood to expose data down the widget tree.

#### Step 1: Define the Model (State Holder)

```dart
class CartItem {
  final String id;
  final String name;
  final double price;
  int quantity;

  CartItem({
    required this.id,
    required this.name,
    required this.price,
    this.quantity = 1,
  });
}
```

#### Step 2: Create the ChangeNotifier (The "Brain")

```dart
import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';

class CartProvider extends ChangeNotifier {
  // Private internal state (Single Source of Truth)
  final List<CartItem> _items = [];

  // Public read-only view (State is Read-Only)
  List<CartItem> get items => List.unmodifiable(_items);

  // Computed property
  double get totalPrice => _items.fold(
    0.0,
    (sum, item) => sum + (item.price * item.quantity),
  );

  // Mutation methods (the ONLY way to change state)
  void addItem(CartItem item) {
    _items.add(item);
    notifyListeners(); // Broadcasts change to UI
  }

  void removeItem(String id) {
    _items.removeWhere((item) => item.id == id);
    notifyListeners();
  }
}
```

#### Step 3: Provide State at the App Root

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:provider/provider.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(
    ChangeNotifierProvider(
      create: (_) => CartProvider(),
      child: const MyApp(),
    ),
  );
}
```

#### Step 4: Consume State in UI (Two Approaches)

```dart
// Approach A: Build-time listening (rebuilds on change)
class CartBadge extends StatelessWidget {
  const CartBadge({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final cart = context.watch<CartProvider>();
    return Badge(label: Text('${cart.items.length}'));
  }
}

// Approach B: Action-only listening (no rebuild)
ElevatedButton(
  onPressed: () => context.read<CartProvider>().addItem(
    CartItem(id: '1', name: 'Phone', price: 999.99),
  ),
  child: const Text('Add to Cart'),
)
```

### 3.3 Data Persistence — SQLite Implementation Walkthrough

#### Step 1: Define Database Schema (SQL DDL)

```sql
CREATE TABLE users (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    email TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    display_name TEXT,
    created_at INTEGER NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE orders (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    user_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    total_amount REAL NOT NULL,
    status TEXT DEFAULT 'pending',
    FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE
);

CREATE INDEX idx_orders_user ON orders(user_id);
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `CREATE INDEX` line is a **KTU high-yield concept** — it accelerates query performance on frequently-filtered columns, exactly the kind of detail examiners love to ask about.

#### Step 2: CRUD Operations in Dart (sqflite)

```dart
class UserRepository {
  final Database _db;

  UserRepository(this._db);

  // CREATE
  Future<int> insertUser(User user) async {
    return _db.insert(
      'users',
      user.toMap(),
      conflictAlgorithm: ConflictAlgorithm.abort,
    );
  }

  // READ with parameterized query (SQL injection safe!)
  Future<List<User>> getUsersByEmail(String email) async {
    final rows = await _db.query(
      'users',
      where: 'email = ?',
      whereArgs: [email],
      limit: 1,
    );
    return rows.map(User.fromMap).toList();
  }

  // UPDATE
  Future<int> updateDisplayName(int id, String newName) async {
    return _db.update(
      'users',
      {'display_name': newName},
      where: 'id = ?',
      whereArgs: [id],
    );
  }

  // DELETE
  Future<int> deleteUser(int id) async {
    return _db.delete('users', where: 'id = ?', whereArgs: [id]);
  }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Security Pitfall (KTU Examiner Loves This):** Never concatenate user input into SQL strings. Always use `?` placeholders with `whereArgs`. Example: `where: 'email = $email'` is **VULNERABLE** to SQL injection.

### 3.4 RESTful API Integration — Step-by-Step (Using Dio in Flutter)

#### Step 1: Define the API Endpoint Contract

```
Base URL:    https://api.example.com/v1
Endpoint:    /users/{id}
Method:      GET
Headers:     Authorization: Bearer <JWT>
Response:    200 OK + JSON { "id": 1, "name": "Alice", ... }
Errors:      401 (no token), 404 (user not found)
```

#### Step 2: Implement the HTTP Client

```dart
import 'package:dio/dio.dart';

class ApiClient {
  late final Dio _dio;

  ApiClient({required String baseUrl}) {
    _dio = Dio(
      BaseOptions(
        baseUrl: baseUrl,
        connectTimeout: const Duration(seconds: 5),
        receiveTimeout: const Duration(seconds: 10),
        headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
      ),
    );

    // Interceptor: Automatically attaches JWT to every request
    _dio.interceptors.add(
      InterceptorsWrapper(
        onRequest: (options, handler) {
          final token = '<JWT_FROM_STORAGE>';
          if (token.isNotEmpty) {
            options.headers['Authorization'] = 'Bearer $token';
          }
          return handler.next(options);
        },
      ),
    );
  }

  // GET request
  Future<Map<String, dynamic>> getUser(int id) async {
    try {
      final response = await _dio.get('/users/$id');
      return response.data;
    } on DioException catch (e) {
      throw _mapDioError(e);
    }
  }

  // POST request
  Future<Map<String, dynamic>> createUser(Map<String, dynamic> body) async {
    try {
      final response = await _dio.post('/users', data: body);
      return response.data;
    } on DioException catch (e) {
      throw _mapDioError(e);
    }
  }

  ApiException _mapDioError(DioException e) {
    switch (e.type) {
      case DioExceptionType.connectionTimeout:
      case DioExceptionType.receiveTimeout:
        return ApiException('Network timeout. Check connection.');
      case DioExceptionType.badResponse:
        return ApiException('Server error: ${e.response?.statusCode}');
      default:
        return ApiException('Unexpected error: ${e.message}');
    }
  }
}
```

#### Step 3: Parse JSON into Domain Model

```dart
class User {
  final int id;
  final String name;
  final String email;

  User({required this.id, required this.name, required this.email});

  // Factory constructor for JSON deserialization
  factory User.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) {
    return User(
      id: json['id'] as int,
      name: json['name'] as String,
      email: json['email'] as String,
    );
  }

  Map<String, dynamic> toJson() => {
    'id': id,
    'name': name,
    'email': email,
  };
}
```

### 3.5 Firebase Integration — Cloud Firestore Walkthrough

#### Step 1: Initialize Firebase in the App

```dart
import 'package:firebase_core/firebase_core.dart';
import 'package:cloud_firestore/cloud_firestore.dart';

void main() async {
  WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized();
  await Firebase.initializeApp(); // Reads google-services.json
  runApp(const MyApp());
}
```

#### Step 2: Firestore CRUD Operations

```dart
class FirestoreService {
  final CollectionReference _usersRef =
      FirebaseFirestore.instance.collection('users');

  // CREATE
  Future<void> addUser(User user) async {
    await _usersRef.doc(user.id.toString()).set(user.toJson());
  }

  // READ (one-time fetch)
  Future<User?> getUser(int id) async {
    final doc = await _usersRef.doc(id.toString()).get();
    if (doc.exists) {
      return User.fromJson(doc.data() as Map<String, dynamic>);
    }
    return null;
  }

  // REAL-TIME READ (Stream — auto-updates UI!)
  Stream<User?> streamUser(int id) {
    return _usersRef
        .doc(id.toString())
        .snapshots()
        .map((doc) =>
            doc.exists ? User.fromJson(doc.data() as Map<String, dynamic>) : null);
  }

  // UPDATE (partial)
  Future<void> updateName(int id, String newName) async {
    await _usersRef.doc(id.toString()).update({'name': newName});
  }

  // DELETE
  Future<void> deleteUser(int id) async {
    await _usersRef.doc(id.toString()).delete();
  }
}
```

#### Step 3: Consume the Stream in UI

```dart
StreamBuilder<User?>(
  stream: firestoreService.streamUser(1),
  builder: (context, snapshot) {
    if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.waiting) {
      return const CircularProgressIndicator();
    }
    if (!snapshot.hasData) return const Text('User not found');
    return Text('Hello, ${snapshot.data!.name}');
  },
)
```

### 3.6 Firebase Authentication — Email/Password Flow

```dart
import 'package:firebase_auth/firebase_auth.dart';

class AuthService {
  final FirebaseAuth _auth = FirebaseAuth.instance;

  // Current user stream (auto-updates login state)
  Stream<User?> get authStateChanges => _auth.authStateChanges();

  // Sign Up
  Future<UserCredential> signUp(String email, String password) async {
    return await _auth.createUserWithEmailAndPassword(
      email: email,
      password: password,
    );
  }

  // Sign In
  Future<UserCredential> signIn(String email, String password) async {
    return await _auth.signInWithEmailAndPassword(
      email: email,
      password: password,
    );
  }

  // Sign Out
  Future<void> signOut() async {
    await _auth.signOut();
  }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why use Streams for auth?** Because `authStateChanges()` automatically emits `null` on logout and a `User` object on login — your UI can simply listen and re-render without manual refresh calls. This is the **reactive paradigm** in action.

