#### Model Solution for Q3 B(a) — REST Architecture and Todo API Design

**Part 1 — REST Principles (3 marks)**

REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style defined by Roy Fielding with these constraints:

1. **Client-Server Separation** — UI is decoupled from data storage.
2. **Statelessness** — Each request contains all info needed; server holds no client session.
3. **Uniform Interface** — Resources identified by URIs, manipulated via standard HTTP verbs.
4. **Cacheability** — Responses can declare themselves cacheable.
5. **Layered System** — Client cannot tell if talking to end server or intermediary.

**Part 2 — Todo API Design (4 marks)**

| # | HTTP Method | URI | Purpose | Status Codes |
|---|-------------|-----|---------|--------------|
| 1 | `GET` | `/api/v1/todos` | Fetch all todos for authenticated user | 200, 401 |
| 2 | `GET` | `/api/v1/todos/{id}` | Fetch a specific todo by ID | 200, 404 |
| 3 | `POST` | `/api/v1/todos` | Create a new todo (body: title, description) | 201, 400 |
| 4 | `PUT` | `/api/v1/todos/{id}` | Replace a todo entirely | 200, 404 |
| 5 | `PATCH` | `/api/v1/todos/{id}` | Partially update (e.g., toggle `completed`) | 200, 404 |
| 6 | `DELETE` | `/api/v1/todos/{id}` | Delete a todo | 204, 404 |

**Example Request-Response for POST /api/v1/todos:**

Request body:
```json
{
  "title": "Complete Milestone 3",
  "description": "Implement state management and persistence",
  "completed": false
}
```

Response (201 Created):
```json
